  "pride_metadata": {
    "project": {
      "accession": "PXD055115",
      "title": "The Cancer Cell Target Discovery. Comparing Laboratory Evolution of Expanded DNA Six-Nucleotide Alphabets with Standard Four-Nucleotide Alphabets",
      "additionalAttributes": [],
      "projectDescription": "Artificial evolvable genetic information systems (AEGIS) are DNA-like molecules that  can be copied, support laboratory in vitro evolution (LIVE), and evolve to give AegisBodies, analogs of antibodies. However, unlike DNA aptamers built from four different nucleotides,  AegisBodies are built from six. Thus, 6-letter AEGIS-LIVE delivers AegisBodies with greater  stability in biological mixtures, more folds, and enhanced binding and catalytic potential.  However, AEGIS has not benefitted from four billion years of biological evolution. To learn  whether AEGIS can nevertheless perform as well as natural DNA, we compare two 6-letter  AegisBodies (LZH5b and LZH8) with a standard 4-letter aptamer. Both were evolved to bind  cancer cells after ~10 cycles of LIVE. Both have ~ 50 nM affinities. Both discovered proteins  on their cancer cell surfaces thought to function only inside of cells. Both can be internalized.  Internalizing of LZH5b attached to an AEGIS nanotrain brings attached drugs into the cell.  These data show that AEGIS-LIVE can do what 4-letter LIVE can do at its limits of  performance after four billion years of evolution. However, synthetic biologists continue to  improve AEGIS, suggesting that AEGIS not be dismissed as an avenue for future  biotechnology.",
      "sampleProcessingProtocol": "The gel pieces were first washed with 50%ACN and 50% water for two times with shaking, and then, the gel pieces were washed for at least three times with 500 \u03bcL of 50% ACN and 50% 100mM NH4HCO3 solution until the gel pieces became colorless. The gel pieces were dried by CAN, and added with 200 \u03bcL of 2 mM TCEP in 50 mM NH4HCO3. After heated to 67 \u2103 for 10 min, the gel pieces were cooled to room temperature, and the TCEP solution was removed. The 10 mM IAA in 50mM NH4HCO3 solution was added, and the system was incubated at room temperature for 30 min in dark. The IAA solution was removed, and the gel pieces were washed with 50 mM NH4HCO3 and ACN for three times. The gel pieces were dried with ACN again. 100\u03bcL of 50 mM NH4HCO3 containing 500 ng Sequencing Grade trypsin was added to the dried gel. After incubated at 4 \u2103 for one hour, another 100 \u03bcL of 50 mM NH4HCO3 was added. The trypsin digestion was incubated overnight at 37\u2103. 50 \u03bcL of pure water was added, and the system was shaked for 15 min. The solution was removed to a new tube. The gel pieces were added with 100 \u03bcL of 5% TFA 60% ACN, and shaked for 15 min. The solution was pooled to the prior eluate. This step was repeated again. Finally, ACN was added, and the solution was pooled again. The eluate was dried by vacuum, and ready for analyses.",
      "dataProcessingProtocol": "The samples were analyzed using an LTQ-Orbitrap Velos Pro mass spectrometer (Thermo Fisher Scientific, USA) coupled with a nanoLC Easy-nLC II, Thermo Fisher Scientific, USA). Each sample was loaded onto a trap column (Easy-column C18-A1, Thermo Fisher Scientific, USA) with phase A (0.1% FA in water). Peptide separation was carried out on a C18 column (Easy-column C18-A2, Thermo Fisher Scientific, USA) at a flow rate of 300 nL/min with a 95 min gradient of 2 to 40% phase B(0.1%FA in acetonitrile) for 70 min, 40 to 95% phase B for 5 min, and 95% phase B for 20 min. The mass spectrometer was operated in positive ionization with the data dependent acquisition (DDA) mode. The parent MS scan was performed in the Orbitrap from a mass range of 350 to 2, 000 m/z with the resolution of 60, 000 at 400 m/z. Top 15 method was used in the automatic switching between MS and MS/MS scans. The MS/MS spectra were acquired with LTQ after the collision-induced dissociation (CID) of nornalized collision energy of 35. Raw files were analyzed using PD2.2.The database search was performed in the Uniprot human protein database, trypsin was chosen as the enzyme with a maximum of two missed cleavages allowed, carbamidomethylation of Cys was set as fixed modifications, and oxidation of Met were set as variable modifications. Other settings were default.",
